John Edward: Global Citizens Need Language Skills
Private schools in Scotland are known to lie at a high academic level, and this continues in 2018 with outstanding exam results, only enhanced by individual and joint success in sports, arts, music and other community activities.
With over 30,000 students throughout Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), are working to offer the best services to their students and parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare their students for further and higher education, career pathways, and roles as global citizens.
As an education sector that can design and implement a tailored curriculum, we see that modern languages are popular choices in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, "If you talk to a man in a language he understands, the message goes to his head.
If you speak to him in his own language, the message goes to his heart."
This is an important reminder that we can't just rely on English when we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries.
Looking at the exam results from this year, we can see that languages are at the top of the league tables with the highest grades for independent schools.
A total of 68 percent of students who took foreign languages received A.
The data, collected from SCIS' 74 member schools, shows that 72 per cent of students received A in mandarin, while 72 per cent of those who took German, 69 per cent of those who took French, and 63 per cent of those who took Spanish also received A.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as vital attributes, which children and young people will definitely need in the future.
Languages as electives are considered equivalent to STEM subjects (science, technology, engineering studies and mathematics) in the curriculum of independent schools and elsewhere.
A 2014 survey conducted by the UK Selection for Addition and Properties showed that 17 percent of employers fail to fill positions due to lack of language skills among applicants.
Therefore, language in school is increasingly important in preparing the youth for work.
With multiple job opportunities for linguists, these qualities are essential in a globalized world.
Regardless of what kind of career a youth chooses, if they have learned a second language, they have a proper advantage in the future with such a trait.
Being able to communicate directly with people from other countries will automatically give a multilingual person advantages in a competitive world.
According to a YouGov survey of more than 4,000 adults in 2013, 75 percent could not speak any language other than English well enough to keep a conversation going, and French was the only language spoken by a two-digit percentage, 15 percent.
This is why it is so important to invest in language training for our children.
Being able to multiple languages, especially the languages used in developing countries, can give children a better chance of finding good jobs in the future.
In Scotland, each school is different when it comes to the language they teach.
Many schools focus on the classical modern languages, while others teach in languages classified as important in the UK as we look forward to 2020, such as Mandarin and Japanese.
Whatever your child is interested in, there will always be a lot of languages to choose from in independent schools, and teachers who are specialists in this area.
Scottish independent schools are dedicated and want to create a learning environment that will prepare children and provide the qualities they need to close, regardless of what the future brings.
One cannot deny that in this global, business-oriented environment, languages are vital to the future of the country, so this must be reflected in the education sector.
Modern languages should be called "international communication properties."
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, thus offering diversity and high competence for Scotland's youth.
We have to do it right.
