Update on dinoflagellates: Decreased concentration in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The latest report from Florida's Fisheries and Wildlife Commission (FWC) shows a general reduction in the concentration of dinoflagellates in the area around Tampa Bay.
According to the FWC, there are reports of unequal conditions for growth in the Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and counties around Collier - suggesting a reduction in concentration.
A growth of dinoflagellates spreads beyond approximately 200 km on the coastline from northern Pinellas to the southern counties of Lee.
Areas with dinoflagellates are found approximately 16 km off the coast of Hillsborough, but compared to the previous week there are fewer areas.
Dinoflagellates have been and have been observed in Pasco.
There have been reports of medium concentration in Pinellas in the past week, low to high concentration along the coast in Hillsborough, low concentration in Manatee, high concentration along the coast in Sarasota, medium concentration in Charlotte, high concentration in Lee and low concentration in Col.
Airway irritation is still reported in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier.
Airway irritation was not reported northwest in Florida last week.
